<bioghist encodinganalog="545">
<p>The Ann Arbor Ministerial Association was established in 1928. Its purpose was to "coordinate the plans and activities of the religious forces of Ann Arbor in regard to all matters of common interest and responsibility, to give united expression to religious conviction and conscience in matters of moral significance and social relationships ..." Some time in the 1940s, a separate organization -- the Ann Arbor Council of Churches -- was formed. The membership of this group included both clergy and laypeople. This organization gradually came to encompass like-minded people beyond Ann Arbor. Accordingly, the name of the organization was changed to the Ann Arbor - Washtenaw Council of Churches.</p>
</bioghist>



<scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
<p>The record group is comprised of two series: Ann Arbor Ministerial Association and Ann Arbor-Washtenaw Council of Churches Yearly Files. The kinds of documents in the Ann Arbor Ministerial Association series includes minutes of meetings, scattered correspondence and financial reports. The Ann Arbor-Washtenaw Council of Churches Yearly Files also includes minutes as well as greater documentation of projects and services provided by the organization.</p>
</scopecontent>

